how serious is it when only one ovary can be found in a woman can it be corrected or can she still have children and finally what does clinical correlation means having one ovary should have no bearing on fertility providing the remaining ovary ovulates and its corresponding fallopian tube is not blocked or having any other issues while two ovaries will alternate each month when there's two of them if you lose one the other one will take over the duties for both the idea that a woman is only fertile every other month with one ovary is a myth having one ovary cannot be corrected there's no such thing as an ovarian transplant clinical correlation means how one medical condition may relate to another condition for example the clinical correlation between obesity and heart disease would be that obesity can lead to heart disease make sense good luck Polycystic ovary syndrome Ovarian cancer Ovary In vitro fertilisation Endometriosis Menstrual cycle Ovulation Hormone replacement therapy (trans) Puberty Intersexuality Androgen insensitivity syndrome Oral contraceptive Ectopic pregnancy Bipolar disorder Lipoid congenital adrenal hyperplasia Medicine Female reproductive system (human) Fertilisation Folic acid Pelvic inflammatory disease Sexual reproduction Obstetrics Sexual differentiation Ovarian cyst Diabetes mellitus Lupus erythematosus Emergency contraception Cancer Gynaecology Amenorrhoea Stem cell Menopause Endocrinology Carpel Atkins Nutritional Approach Fertility awareness Intersex surgery Cardiovascular disease Stomach cancer Hypercholesterolemia Ovarian hyperstimulation syndrome Breastfeeding Fruit Spina bifida Human sexuality National Institutes of Health Asthma Alternative medicine Electrocardiogram Autism Flowering plant Abortion debate Non-Hodgkin's lymphoma Congenital adrenal hyperplasia due to 17 alpha-hydroxylase deficiency Milk History of sex Breast cancer Prostate cancer Anorexia nervosa Sex reassignment surgery female-to-male Multiple sclerosis Sterilizati